  "paragraphs": [
    [
      {
        "text": "The six inhabited "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara islands",
        "entity_key": "i_chi",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " off "
      },
      {
        "text": "the coast",
        "entity_key": "re_socalcoast",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " of Southern California were equally divided between "
      },
      {
        "text": "Indians of the Chumash",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Shoshonean stocks",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". The three northern islands, "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Miguel",
        "entity_key": "i_sm",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Rosa",
        "entity_key": "i_sr",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Cruz",
        "entity_key": "i_scruz",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", adjoining the coast of "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "co_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " and "
      },
      {
        "text": "Ventura",
        "entity_key": "co_ventura",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " counties, were occupied, like "
      },
      {
        "text": "this coast strip",
        "entity_key": "re_socalcoast",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", by "
      },
      {
        "text": "Chumash",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", whose family appellation, which is only a book name, is derived from the native term for "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Rosa",
        "entity_key": "i_sr",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " or "
      },
      {
        "text": "its inhabitants",
        "entity_key": "natam_Chumash",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". The three southern islands, "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Catalina",
        "entity_key": "i_scatalina",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Clemente",
        "entity_key": "i_scl",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and the outlying "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", were held by "
      },
      {
        "text": "Shoshoneans",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ".1 "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Catalina",
        "entity_key": "i_scatalina",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " was occupied by "
      },
      {
        "text": "people speaking Gabrielino",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and its name was Pimu. "
      },
      {
        "text": "The Luiseño",
        "entity_key": "natam_Luisenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "call the island "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Catalina",
        "entity_key": "i_scatalina",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " Pipimar. The affiliations of "
      },
      {
        "text": "the inhabitants of San Clemente",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " are not certain. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Reid",
        "entity_key": "hre",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " includes "
      },
      {
        "text": "the island",
        "entity_key": "i_scl",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", under the name Kinkipar, in his list of the principal rancherias of the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Gabrielino \"Indians of Los Angeles county.\"",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "The present "
      },
      {
        "text": "Gabrielino Indians",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " call the island Kinki, "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Luiseño",
        "entity_key": "natam_Luisenos",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " call it Khesh; "
      },
      {
        "text": "the latter",
        "entity_key": "natam_GabrilenoTongva",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": " state that it was inhabited by people speaking their own language, who, after having been brought to "
      },
      {
        "text": "the mainland",
        "entity_key": "re_mld",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " by "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Franciscans",
        "entity_key": "misfats",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ", were settled at a place three miles below "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Luis Rey Mission",
        "entity_key": "mi_sl",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", to which they gave the same name, Khesh. "
      },
      {
        "text": "That ",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas island",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ],
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " was inhabited by Shoshoneans is evident from the four words preserved of the language of ",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the last survivor",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", a woman who was alone on ",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the island",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ],
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " for eighteen years and died soon after being brought to ",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the mainland",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ],
        "entity_key": "re_mld",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " half a century ago.",
        "tropes": [
          6
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "2 These four words are: man, nache; sky, toygwah; hide, tocah; body, puoo-chay. Toygwah is certainly Shoshonean, as will be seen from a glance at the comparative vocabulary. The place of the "
      },
      {
        "text": "San Nicolas island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": "dialect in the general classification of the Shoshonean family cannot, however, be determined from this scanty material, especially as the spelling is English and there is no evidence that the four words are free from errors of typography or copying. It is not impossible that the dialect was fairly close to Gabrielino or Luiseño3, or, on the other hand, that it was much differentiated from all others."
      }
    ]
  ]
}